Subject: [PATCH] C-9: STW root-evacuation move in the real JVM (StoplessGC)

First in-JVM integration of the moving collector (the concurrent algorithm is
already proven standalone in cap_runtime tests/test_concurrent_move). At a
safepoint (System.gc() -> StoplessHeap::collect -> VM_StoplessCollect):
  1. scan_roots with StoplessMoveRootsClosure: for each root oop IN the arena,
     relocate it to a fresh arena slot (StoplessHeap::move_object — a
     capability-preserving HeapWord=16B word copy, preserving data + oop-field
     tags; keeps the original mark/klass, no init_mark), record old->new in the
     shared forward_table (cas_insert), and update the root slot to the new cap.
  2. revoke every moved-from object (StoplessArena mark_for_revoke + revoke_sweep)
     -> any surviving stale reference (e.g. a heap field still pointing at the
     old copy) faults on next access and the C-7 SIGPROT handler forwards it via
     the forward_table.
StoplessHeap::initialize now calls forward_table_init (the table the handler
reads). A move LIMIT (env STOPLESS_MOVE_LIMIT, default 8) keeps this first cut
low-risk.

RESULT: java -XX:+UseStoplessGC HelloGC (println + System.gc()) ->
  [Stopless] C-9 STW collect: moved=8 fixed_roots=17 nonheap_roots=0 revoked=8
  exit=0
i.e. the live JVM relocated 8 arena objects, revoked the old copies, and ran to
completion — the SIGPROT handler transparently forwarded every stale reference
to a moved object. End-to-end moving GC in a purecap JVM. The concurrent
collector thread (off-safepoint, mutator-assisted) layers on this next.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

